<p><a href="#sdfootnote8anc" name="sdfootnote8sym">8</a> These are the main reasons behind the poor condition of Polish cinema during the country’s transformation period suggested by Piotr Marecki. Moreover, free-market transition in the field of film compelled the most important filmmakers – Andrzej Wajda, Kazimierz Kutz – to adopt conservative positions while preserving “vocabulary, ideology, and iconographic package faithful to tradition.” Another catastrophe was brought about by the re-organization of the working system: the cessation of crews managed by both an artistic and a literary head, in order to consolidate the film director’s position (who often acted as a producer). See: Piotr Marecki, “<em>Nad rzeką, której nie ma</em> Andrzeja Barańskiego, czyli przyliteracki status kina,” in <em>Kino polskie 1989–2009. Historia krytyczna</em>, eds. Agnieszka Wiśniewska and Piotr Marecki (Warsaw: Wydawnictwo Krytyki Politycznej, 2010), 12–13.</p>
