<p><a href="#sdfootnote22anc" name="sdfootnote22sym">22</a> Term borrowed from Magda Szcześniak. “Norms of visibility” are defined as a complex system of practices and models of “normality” generated by the middle class, which is “founded primarily on the mechanism of differentiation and exclusion – drawing a boundary between what is recognized as normal and what is abnormal, or in visual categories – between learnt transparency and excess, surplus, exaggeration, vulgarity, manifestation, and – the flip side of the coin – invisibility, removal from the field of vision.” See: Szcześniak, <em>Normy widzialności</em>, 23.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote23anc" name="sdfootnote23sym">23</a> Szcześniak<em>, Normy widzialności</em>, 88–89.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote24anc" name="sdfootnote24sym">24</a> See: Jakub Majmurek, “III RP, czyli dwie cele wstydu,” <em>Krytyka Polityczna</em>, July 13, 2013, <a href="https://krytykapolityczna.pl/kraj/majmurek-iii-rp-czyli-dwie-cele-wstydu/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://krytykapolityczna.pl/kraj/majmurek-iii-rp-czyli-dwie-cele-wstydu/</a> (accessed February 19, 2019).</p>
