<p><a href="#sdfootnote26anc" name="sdfootnote26sym">26</a> Marecki and Kletowski, <em>Królikiewicz</em>, 312.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote27anc" name="sdfootnote27sym">27</a> The “long lasting” of communism in the democratic structures of power was depicted several years previously by Władysław Pasikowski. Yet in his <em>Pigs</em> (1992), the filmmaker was interested primarily in the conflict within the state apparatus, embroiled in the machinations of the business demimonde. It is not by chance that his film barely represents the ordinary citizen, because such a figure was supposed to retain the comfortable distance of the viewer who formulates opinions and remains outside the spectacle. The “pact” was supposed to remain beyond the viewer, unrelated to his or her social conditions. For that reason, Pasikowski’s critique embraced merely one aspect of the problem of the Polish transformation, and was not supposed to lead, I believe, to challenging the legitimacy of the “shock therapy,” based on the anachronistic myth of the self-made man, and such conclusions could have been drawn if the viewer recognized themselves on the screen as the victim of political transformation, stripped of agency. Meanwhile, in <em>The Trees</em>, the topic of social harm inflicted by the elites is the very essence of the film, which therefore comes across as a much more radical diagnosis of Poland after 1989.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote28anc" name="sdfootnote28sym">28</a> Marecki and Kletowski, <em>Królikiewicz</em>, 314.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote29anc" name="sdfootnote29sym">29</a> Marecki and Kletowski, <em>Królikiewicz</em>, 315.</p></div>

				

				
